    stimulus: 'In her analysis of urban migration patterns in twentieth-century West Africa, historian Chisom Eze distinguishes between "push" and "pull" factors. Push factors are conditions that drive people away from their places of origin — drought, land scarcity, political instability — while pull factors are conditions that attract migrants to destination cities — wage labor, educational opportunities, family networks already established there. Eze argues that earlier scholarship overemphasized push factors, portraying migrants as passive victims of hardship, and underestimated the degree to which migrants made active, calculated decisions based on perceived opportunities in cities. She does not deny that push factors existed; she argues only that they do not fully explain the patterns of who migrated, when, and where.',
    question: 'Based on Eze\'s argument, which of the following best describes how she views earlier scholarship on urban migration?',
